% Density of the Poor
To measure the size of the poor, we follow a similar strategy presented in \citet{Weitz-shapiro}, measuring the degree of poverty at the municipal level. Using information from the 2010 Brazilian census\footnote{Official data comes from the Bureau of Statistics of Brazil \href{http://www.ibge.gov.br}{IBGE}.}, a variable that measures the percentage of individuals who live with less than half of the minimum wage was constructed. Given that we observe the municipality of residence for each individual in the survey, we were able to merge that percentage with the LAPOP dataset. Although this value was originally a semi-continuous variable, it had to be dichotomized at the median (\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(median(m.data$wagehalf)), 2)}\%) to be able to construct the matched sample. There have been theoretical advances regarding general treatment effects regimes for continuous or semi-continuous response doses (\citet{Ratkovic2012}, \citet{Hirano2004}), algorithms capable to match on continuous treatment variables are not common. \autoref{fig:tgraph:plot} shows the continuous distribution dichotomized at the median (dashed line). However, we still provide alternative specifications using the original continuous variable as a robustness, weighting on the generalized propensity score (see \citet{Imbens2004}, \citet{Guardabascio2014} and \citet[]{Imai2014b})\footnote{To generate the weighting vector, we used the \texttt{CBPS R} package (\citet{Fong:2014aa}).}. The advantage of this strategy is that it does not require dichotomization. The same covariates used in the \texttt{CEM} matching procedure were used to create the \texttt{GPS} weighting vector.


