% Political Competition // Income
To measure political competition, the paper follows \citet[]{Weitz-shapiro}. Using official electoral data for the 2008 municipal elections\footnote{\href{http://agencia.tse.jus.br/estatistica/sead/odsele/votacao_candidato_munzona/votacao_candidato_munzona_2008.zip}{Tribunal Superior Eleitoral}.}, a variable that measures the percentage of seats that are not controlled by the mayor's party in a given municipal council was constructed. Though the survey provides a question for income, people who are somewhat better off than their neighbors but live in poor areas may not ``feel'' poor. If this is the case, this could confound the results\footnote{I thank the reviewers of LAPS for this suggestion.}. Also, when answering the questioner, individuals might not want to reveal their true incomes (either because it is too low or too high). Following the advice of \citet{Cordova2008,Cordova2009,Cordova2010}, a relative wealth index (RWI) was constructed. Using principal component analyses, this index measures wealth based on actual assets weighted by how common those assets are. Different indexes were constructed for urban and rural contexts.


\subsection*{Outcome Variable}


% our dependent variable is the proportion of fixations, during the ambiguous region, to the animal (the potential recipient, e.g., the horse). This captures the degree to which participants expect the recipient rather than the theme. [...] Following Barr (2008), proportion of fixations to the animal and the object were first empirical logit-transformed [...]

Clientelism was measured using the question that asks if \emph{a candidate or someone from a political party offered [the respondent] something, like a favor, food, or any other benefit or thing in return for [her/his] vote or support?} Subjects could answer whether this had happened \emph{often}, \emph{sometimes} or \emph{never}. \citet[]{Carreras2013a} and \citet[]{Holland2015} use the same dataset and outcome variable. As they explain, the question did not ask if respondents \emph{took} the offer, hence it should not be an important source of bias. In order to have a dichotomous response variable, the alternatives \emph{often} (\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(m.data$clientelism)["Often"])}) and \emph{sometimes} (\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(m.data$clientelism)["Sometimes"])}) were collapsed into one, leaving \emph{never} (\Sexpr{as.numeric(table(m.data$clientelism)["Never"])}) unchanged.


\subsection*{Control Variables}

% Why I included the control variables I included

%Following the advice of \citet{Ho2006}, the same set of covariates in the matching procedure were used in the parametric stage. I DONT SAY THIS SINCE IN THE MATCHING PART I INCLUDED urban and in the parametric MUN POP.

Perception of Corruption was included so as to keep constant the effect of respondents who declared clientelistic activity when in reality they were referring to corruption scandals\footnote{I thank Cesar Zucco for this suggestion.}. \citet[]{Rueda2014a,Holland2015,Carreras2013} argue that brokers target civic associations. Following \citet[p. 28]{Holland2015}, who use the same dataset/year, an additive index to measure civic participation (\emph{Political Involvement}) was created\footnote{This variable was constructed adding up the frequency of attendance at religious organizations, community improvement committees and political party meetings (variables \texttt{cp6}, \texttt{cp8} and \texttt{cp13}, respectively).}. Group size has also been claimed to be important (\citet[]{Stokes2005,Kitschelt2007}). Smaller communities are easier to monitor (\citet[]{Rueda2014a}). Using census data, a variable to measure population size at the municipal level was included. Building on some of the distributive politics literature, following particularly \citet{Stokes2005}, \citet{Dixit1996} and \citet{Nichter2008}, a variable that captures party identification (\emph{Political Id.}) was included. The idea was to control for core/swinger targeting. Higher levels of democratic support should be negatively associated with clientelism (\citet{Carlin2015}). Using the same dataset, a variable measuring democratic support was included. \citet{GonzalezOcantos2014} finds that schooling plays a negative role on clientelism, hence we control for educational levels too.


\subsection*{Estimation Method}

% introducing
This paper is concerned about the likelihood of an individual, conditioned on several factors, to receive clientelism. Individuals (the unit of analysis) are clustered around a  number of important factors such as levels of municipal political competition, municipal poverty and municipal population size. In order to account for the clustering effects these factors have on individuals, logistic GEE regression were fitted. Generalized estimating equations were introduced by \citet{Liang1986} to fit clustered, repeated (i.e. correlated) and panel data. The method is especially well suited when the data are binary (\citet{Hanley2003a}). GEE models are similar to random effects (\citet{Gardiner2009}) in that they allow observations to be nested in hierarchical structures. This method requires analysts to parameterize the working correlation matrix. Though \citet[p. 139]{Hedeker2006} explain that ``the GEE is robust to misspecification of the correlation structure''\footnote{\citet[p. 402]{Carlin2001}, argue that ``[r]elatively minor differences in estimates may arise depending on how the estimating equations are weighted, in particular within the generalized estimating equation (GEE) framework''. \citet{Westgate2016} and \citet[p. 227]{Gardiner2009} make the same point.}, \citet[p. 166]{Hardin2013} point out that ``[i]f the observations are clustered (not collected over time), then [...] the exchangeable correlation structure'' is the most appropriated working correlation matrix. Given that our dataset rather follow a clustered structure, we fit GEE logistic models using both the raw dataset (weighted by the GPS) and the matched datasets assuming an exchangeable correlation matrix.

% gee problems // simulation
Though GEE methods have several advantages due to its flexibility, as in any random-effect type of model, their estimates remain in practice uninterpretable (\citet{Carlin2001}), making regression tables useless from a substantive standpoint. In our case, the problem is even more severe due to the interactive hypotheses being tested in this paper. The main hypothesis is tested by fitting a parameter for the multiplication between the variables \texttt{wealth index}, \texttt{political competition} and \texttt{high density}. Methodologists agree on ``not to interpret the coefficients on the constitutive terms'', as they lack substantive meaning (\citet[p. 77]{Brambor2005}). These problems get more complex when it comes to generalized models. A series of challenges arise. As \citet{Ai2003} explain, \emph{(1) the interaction effect could be nonzero, even when the estimation says it is zero, (2) the statistical significance of the interaction effect cannot be tested with a simple t-test on the coefficient of the interaction term, (3) the interaction effect is conditional on the independent variables, [...] and (4) the interaction effect may have different signs for different values of covariates}. \citet[p. 74]{Brambor2005} offer the same advice, i.e. ``one cannot determine whether a model should include an interaction term simply by looking at the significance of the coefficient on the interaction term''. Given that cross-partial derivatives are not advisable either, simulation methods are required (\citet[]{WilliamJ.Wales2013}). Particularly, we follow the simulation approach introduced in \citet{King2000}\footnote{\citet{Lam:2011aa} in \citet{Imai:2009vn}.}. This procedure samples from the point estimates (via simulation) generating a new larger distribution. That is, taking the single estimated parameters (the regression coefficients) we construct a distribution of estimated values for each. Relying on the central limit theorem, with enough sampling draws, the new simulated distribution is a transformation that approximates with great degree of precision the (uninterpretable) coefficients. Then, means and uncertainty measures can be constructed for each of these distributions. From a substantive standpoint, simulation methods also allow sampling new distributions at different values of the independent variables. This will be important to simulate the expected value of clientelism for different ``profiles'', such as \emph{non}-poor individuals nested in \emph{high}-poor dense municipalities in contexts of \emph{high} political competition, and others.

\section*{Results} 

Since it is ``impossible to evaluate conditional hypotheses using only the information provided in traditional results tables'' (\citet[p. 76]{Brambor2005}) we rather focus on the substantive results using simulation methods. However, we still present the raw results in \autoref{tab:1} in the Appendix\footnote{Table generated via the \texttt{texreg R} package.}. The first column shows the estimates for the matched dataset while the second column shows the results for the GPS wighted model. Given that virtually all coefficients have the same size and sign, for simplicity, all simulations were performed sampling from the models with the matched dataset. \autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants} shows evidence for the theoretical model presented in \autoref{tab:strategy:set}.


