\subsection*{Density of the Poor, Political Competition and Income} 

% explain graph
Analogously to \autoref{tab:strategy:set}, \autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants} is divided in two panels, for when political competition is high/low and for when individuals are poor/non-poor\footnote{The left panel simulates values for the lower quartile (25\%) while the right panel simulates values for the upper quartile (75\%) of the continuous \texttt{wealth index} variable. The upper panel simulates values for the minimum value of the continuous variable political competition (\Sexpr{min(m.data$munopp)}\%), while the lower panel simulates values for the maximum value (\Sexpr{max(m.data$munopp)}\%) of the same variable.}. For each of these four combinations, we plotted two simulated distributions of the expected values of clientelism. One for when individuals are nested in contexts of high poverty density and one for low poverty nesting.  


% present the results: intro
The first result is that we find support for \citet{Weitz-shapiro}'s paper, i.e. higher levels of political competition move the probability of receiving clientelism upwards. This probability as expected is conditional on municipal poverty levels. However we also find that wealth reverses the direction in which the density of the poor is associated to clientelism. For example, going from quadrant 4 to quadrant 1 makes poor individuals nested in \emph{non}-poor municipalities (i.e. low poverty density) and exposed to \emph{low} political competition levels \emph{more} likely to be targeted. We also find that clientelism also exists under low-competition levels. 

% present the results: 1
\autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants} suggests that brokers engage in \emph{individual} clientelism by targeting poor individuals nested in low-dense municipalities (quadrant 1, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(mean(low.poor.lowcomp$x)*100,0)}\% of being targeted), while they target non-poor individuals in high-poor dense municipalities (quadrant 4, with a probability of \Sexpr{round(mean(high.rich.highcomp$x)*100,0)}\% of being targeted). Clientelism is higher in the latter case because higher electoral pressures incentive motivated brokers to mobilize more electoral support. Inside quadrant 1, the simulated distribution for individuals nested in low-poor density municipalities is consistently larger than the individuals in the high-poor condition. 


% HERE


According to the Wilcoxon rank sum independence test for non-normal distributions, individuals in the high poverty context (\Sexpr{round(mean(high.poor.lowcomp$x)*100,0)}\% of being targeted) have systematically less probabilities of being targeted compared  to individuals in the low density context. \emph{Group} targeting is more efficient in quadrants 2 and 3. Particularly in the latter, brokers take advantage of the spillover effects of clientelism. In these settings, low-income individuals nested in poor municipalities provide enough economies of scale making brokers to abandon individual targeting. Every unit invested in clientelism is then multiplied when both actual \emph{and} potential voters are electorally mobilized. Given the faster discount rates of low-income individuals and the necessity of politicians to gather more electoral support, we expected clientelism to be the highest. Though we find a high probability of being targeted (\Sexpr{round(mean(high.poor.highcomp$x)*100,0)}\%), it is very close to the low density individuals in quadrant 4. However, a Wilcoxon rank sum independence test suggests 


Finally, we were expecting non-poor individuals nested in low-poor dense municipalities under low political competition levels (quadrant 2) to have the lowest probability of being targeted. We find that these individuals have a probability of being targeted of \Sexpr{round(mean(low.rich.lowcomp$x)*100, 0)}\%. However, this distribution is skewed to the right, shifting the mean upwards, and also with very heavy tails. Quadrant 2 hence suggests a diffuse pattern, which is the null finding we were expecting.


\subsection*{Population Size and Organization Buying}

% introduction, say what the problem is, introduce the graph
So far we have introduced the idea that brokers shift targeting strategies, directing their resources to individuals or groups depending on the levels of (un)certainty each strategy presents. That is, how identifiable individuals are. Individuals are easier to identify in situations when low-income individuals live in low-dense poverty contexts and when non-poor individuals live in high-poor density municipalities. The more identifiable individuals are, the cheaper individual targeting is. When the reverse happens, group targeting is the best strategy, specially when brokers can take advantage of spillover effects. It also plays a role how electorally pressured political parties are. When politicians feel more contested, brokers will have clear incentives to secure more votes, even targeting the non-poor. Though the theory focuses on targeting, by \emph{explicitly} considering macro explanations, such as the role of the density of the poor on clientelism, this argument is novel. We agree with \citet{Carlin2015}, in that the vote-buying literature consistently looks at individual explanations (only)\footnote{\citet{Weitz-shapiro}, \citet{Rueda2014a} and others are great exceptions.}. One of the secondary objectives of this paper is to explicitly incorporate those factors, particularly by systematizing the incentives parties have. This section tests against the density of the poor, one individual-level variable (political involvement) and one macro-variable (population size), both being highly recurrent in the literature. 

% analyze the graph
\autoref{fig:pol.inv:pop.size:plot} shows a plot divided in two panels. Panel \emph{a} shows simulated expected values of receiving clientelism at different levels of political involvement. As the blue lines suggests, individuals who participate in civic associations have higher probabilities of being targeted. This is in line with findings in previous research (\citet{Schaffer2015}, \citet[p. 7]{Carreras2013}, \citet{Calvo2012}, \citet[p. 16]{Holland2015} and \citet[]{Rueda2014a}). However, once we decompose these effects, we see that being nested in high-dense areas contributes substantially more to the model. These differences are statistically significant. Panel \emph{b} shows the probability of being targeted given increments in the size of the population where individuals are nested. In line with the literature, we also see that this relation is negative (\citet[323]{Stokes2005}, \citet[10]{Kitschelt2007}, \citet[p. 67]{Magaloni:2008bq}, \citet{Rueda2016}, \citet[]{Bratton2008a} and \citet[p. 456]{Gingerich2013}). However, the effect of being nested in high-poor dense municipalities outperform the effects of population size, suggesting spillover effects (even when income/wealth and political competition are held constants). What this exercise tells us is two folds. First, it is important to consider macro explanations of vote-buying, as they shape brokers' incentive structures when deciding when and who to target. All in all, structural factors such as the density of the poor and political competition, are one of the few and perhaps only observable factors brokers have to make decisions where to invest in clientelism. Second, population size does shift the costs of clientelism. Larger populations carry more coordination dilemmas, increasing the probability of defection, making clientelism an unsafe strategy for brokers (as panel \emph{b} suggests). However, as we have seen in this paper, these costs are alleviated when brokers take advantages of the spillover effects of clientelism (\autoref{fig:plot:four:quadrants}). This strongly suggests that there are some costs that matter more than others. We have suggested this idea twice in this article: it is not clear how ``moral costs'' refrain democratic \emph{but} poor individuals from engaging in clientelism, and it is also not clear how ``coordination costs'' deter brokers, considering that large-sized groups potentially provide greater electoral support. As we have argued here, coordination costs should be alleviated by resorting to group targeting and taking advantage of the spillover effects of clientelism.


